## 2. Factors Influencing Effectiveness

### 2.1 Time on Task and Blended Learning

The U.S. Department of Education report highlighted two critical factors positively impacting learning outcomes:

| Factor                   | Description                                                                                   |
|--------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Time Spent Studying       | Online learners often spend more total time engaging with course materials and activities.    |
| Blended Learning          | Combining online and face-to-face instruction tends to produce better outcomes than either alone.|

This underscores that instructional design and learner engagement are more influential than the delivery medium per se ([Means et al., 2009](https://www.ed.gov/rschstat/eval/tech/evidence-based-practices/finalreport.pdf)).

### 2.2 Instructional Design and Interaction

John Hattie's synthesis of over 800 studies emphasizes factors like formative evaluation, teaching clarity, feedback, and teacher-student relationships as paramount to student achievement (Hattie, 2008). These elements can be effectively integrated into both online and face-to-face environments, but require intentional design.

Poorly structured online courses with confusing navigation or limited interaction can hinder learning, while well-designed online courses with frequent assessments and timely feedback can enhance it (Croasmun, 2014).

